{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524874"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:09:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.13,0.13,0.52,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49861"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6683"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49861"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, productive cough, and increasing shortness of breath. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, gout, dyslipidaemia and osteoarthritis. His regular medications include ramipril, metformin, rosuvastatin, allopurinol and chlorthalidone. On examination, he appears unwell with a JVP at the base of the neck, pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals crackles in the right lower zone. Investigations reveal a creatine kinase (CK) and serum potassium within normal limits, but a serum creatinine of 145 \u03bcmol/L (60-110).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following medications should be withheld on admission?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ramipril, rosuvastatin and allopurinol","Ramipril, rosuvastatin, allopurinol and chlorthalidone","Ramipril, metformin, rosuvastatin and allopurinol","Ramipril, metformin, allopurinol and chlorthalidone","Ramipril, metformin, rosuvastatin, allopurinol and chlorthalidone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate medication combination to withhold is: \u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril, metformin, allopurinol and chlorthalidone \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERamipril (ACE inhibitor) should be withheld given the patient\u0027s hypotension. ACE inhibitors can exacerbate hypotension and reduce renal perfusion. Restarting this medication (at reduced or full dose) can be considered later in the admission if the patient improves or on discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChlorthalidone (thiazide-like diuretic) should be withheld given the patient\u0027s hypotension and likely hypovolaemic volume status, both of which would be exacerbated by such a medication with diuretic and anti-hypertensive properties. Restarting this medication (at reduced or full dose) can be considered later in the admission if the patient improves or on discharge. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMetformin, whilst an effective medication for type 2 diabetes, can accumulate in renal impairment and can also potentially cause lactic acidosis, a rare but serious complication. If the patient had issues with hyperglycaemia during admission, a supplemental insulin scale could be used as a temporary measure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAllopurinol (xanthine oxidase inhibitor) used in gout, should be withheld or at least dose reduced in patients with renal impairment. The medication contains a renally-excreted active metabolite that accumulates in renal impairment and may cause adverse effects if not withheld or dose-reduced. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELipid-lowering agents such as rosuvastatin carry an increased risk of rhabdomyolysis with renal impairment and such should be withheld if the AKI is due to rhabdomyolysis. Given the patient\u0027s CK is within normal limits, it is reasonable to continue rosuvastatin with close monitoring and consideration of cessation if the patient develops unexplained/persistent muscle pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephrotoxic medications should be withheld in acutely unwell patients with potential acute kidney injury.","Careful medication review is essential when admitting patients with acute illness to prevent further kidney damage."],"references":["Practitioners TRAC of general. Prescribing for older people with chronic renal impairment [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. 2013. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/january-february/prescribing-for-older-people-with-cri"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T11:57:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T11:58:31+09:30"},"relatio